  "response": "Here are some highly recommended Python books for absolute beginners:\n\n1. \"Python Crash Course\" by Eric Matthes\n- Excellent for complete beginners\n- Practical projects and clear explanations\n- Covers fundamentals and introduces real-world programming\n\n2. \"Automate the Boring Stuff with Python\" by Al Sweigart\n- Very beginner-friendly\n- Focuses on practical applications\n- Free online version available\n- Great for learning through practical tasks\n\n3. \"Learning Python\" by Mark Lutz\n- Comprehensive and in-depth\n- Detailed explanations\n- Suitable for those who want a thorough understanding\n\n4. \"Head First Python\" by Paul Barry\n- Visual and engaging learning approach\n- Uses graphics and unique teaching style\n- Makes learning fun and interactive\n\n5. \"Introduction to Python Programming\" by Brad Miller and David Ranum\n- Gentle introduction\n- Interactive online version available\n- Good for self-paced learning\n\nOnline Alternatives:\n- Codecademy Python Course\n- freeCodeCamp Python tutorials\n- Coursera Python specializations\n\nRecommendation for absolute beginners:\n\"Python Crash Course\" or \"Automate the Boring Stuff\" are typically the most accessible and practical for newcomers.",
